'''Rúben dos Santos Gato Alves Dias''' (born 14 May 1997) is a Portuguese professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[centre-back]] for {{English football updater|ManchesC}} club [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] and the [[Portugal national football team|Portugal national team]]. He is regarded as one of the best centre-backs in the world.<ref>Multiple sources:
*{{Cite web |last1=Altimas |first1=Callum |last2=Ritchie |first2=Calum |date=9 October 2023 |title=The 20 best defenders in world football right now – ranked in order |url=https://www.givemesport.com/best-defenders-world-football-ranked/ |access-date=29 March 2025 |website=GiveMeSport}}
*{{Cite web |date=15 September 2023 |title=Ranked! The 10 best centre-backs in the world |url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/best-centre-backs-defenders-in-the-world |access-date=29 March 2025 |website=fourfourtwo.com}}
*{{Cite web |date=9 March 2020 |title=The 25 best centre backs in world football – ranked |url=https://www.90min.com/posts/6573230-the-25-best-centre-backs-in-world-football-ranked |access-date=29 March 2025 |website=90min.com}}</ref>

Dias came through [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]]'s youth academy. He began playing for [[S.L. Benfica B|Benfica B]] in 2015 and was promoted to the first-team in 2017, and was named the [[2017–18 Primeira Liga#Annual awards|Primeira Liga's Young Player of the Year]]. The following season, Dias won the [[2018–19 Primeira Liga|league title]] in the [[2018–19 S.L. Benfica season|2018–19 season]] with [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] and later the [[2019 Supertaça Cândido de Oliveira|Supertaça Cândido de Oliveira]] during the [[2019–20 S.L. Benfica season|2019–20 season]], while also being named in the [[2019–20 Primeira Liga#Annual awards|Primeira Liga's Team of the Year]], making over 100 appearances in the process.

He signed for Premier League club [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in September 2020 for a reported fee of €68&nbsp;million, becoming the second-highest fee for a Portuguese player leaving the domestic league. Dias won the [[2020–21 Premier League|league title]] and [[2020–21 EFL Cup|EFL Cup]] in his first season, while also reaching the [[2021 UEFA Champions League final|UEFA Champions League final]]. He was also named [[FWA Footballer of the Year]], [[List of Manchester City F.C. players#Player of the Year awards|Manchester City Player of the Year]], [[Premier League Player of the Season]] and the [[UEFA Club Football Awards#Best Defender|UEFA Champions League Defender of the Season]] in 2021. In [[2022–23 Manchester City F.C. season|2022–23]], he played a crucial role as City secured a first-ever [[Treble (association football)|continental treble]], their most successful season to date.

Dias is a former [[Portugal national youth football team|Portugal youth international]], representing his country at [[Portugal national under-16 football team|under-16]], [[Portugal national under-17 football team|under-17]], [[Portugal national under-19 football team|under-19]], [[Portugal national under-20 football team|under-20]] and [[Portugal national under-21 football team|under-21]] levels. He made his senior international debut in 2018, being chosen in Portugal's squads for two [[FIFA World Cup]]s ([[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018]] and [[2022 FIFA World Cup|2022]]) and two [[UEFA European Championship]]s ([[UEFA Euro 2020|2020]] and [[UEFA Euro 2024|2024]]); he also won the [[2019 UEFA Nations League Finals|2019]] and [[2025 UEFA Nations League Finals]], being named in the [[2019 UEFA Nations League Finals#Awards|2019 team of the tournament]] on home soil and man of the match in the [[2019 UEFA Nations League final|final]].

==Early life==
Rúben dos Santos Gato Alves Dias<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tournament.fifadata.com/documents/FWC/2018/pdf/FWC_2018_SQUADLISTS.PDF|title=FIFA World Cup Russia 2018: List of Players: Portugal|publisher=FIFA|date=15 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191206135930/https://tournament.fifadata.com/documents/FWC/2018/pdf/FWC_2018_SQUADLISTS.PDF|archive-date=6 December 2019}}</ref> was born on 14 May 1997<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/player/_/id/234878/ruben-dias |title=Rúben Dias: Overview |publisher=ESPN |access-date=28 September 2020}}</ref> in [[Amadora]], Lisbon District.<ref name="Soccerway">{{cite web |url=https://uk.soccerway.com/players/ruben-dias/290253/ |title=Rúben Dias: Summary |website=Soccerway |publisher=Perform Group |access-date=28 September 2020}}</ref> He has an older brother Ivan, who is also a professional football player, who nicknamed him "Ruby".<ref name=earlyLigfe>{{Cite web|url=https://lifebogger.com/pt/hist%C3%B3ria-da-inf%C3%A2ncia-de-Ruben-Dias-mais-fatos-incont%C3%A1veis-%E2%80%8B%E2%80%8Bda-biografia/|title=Ruben Dias Childhood Story Plus Untold Biografia Fatos|first=Hale|last=Hendrix|date=16 October 2020|website=LifeBogger|access-date=31 October 2021|archive-date=1 November 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211101052455/https://lifebogger.com/pt/hist%C3%B3ria-da-inf%C3%A2ncia-de-Ruben-Dias-mais-fatos-incont%C3%A1veis-%E2%80%8B%E2%80%8Bda-biografia/|url-status=dead}}</ref> Growing up, his idols were [[John Terry]], [[Nemanja Vidić]], [[Rio Ferdinand]], and [[Vincent Kompany]], whom he looked to emulate, as he aspired to play in the [[Premier League]] from an early age. He would play football wherever he could on the streets or in his house with his brother Ivan.<ref name=Dias10facts>{{cite video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VeKF1SCrqOM&ab_channel=SoccerStories-OhMyGoal|title=10 things you didn't know about Ruben Dias|author=Oh My Goal|via=YouTube|access-date=22 May 2021}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Benfica B===
Dias started his career at local club [[C.F. Estrela da Amadora|Estrela da Amadora]] after being brought to the club by a close family member.<ref name=earlyLigfe/> Dias initially played as a striker, before switching to defence, due to his team being losing by two goals during a match.<ref name=Dias10facts/><ref name=lifefacts>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mancity.com/news/mens/ruben-dias-factfile-career-stats-63736979|title=Ruben Dias: Things you need to know|first=John|last=Edwards|date=29 September 2020|website=mancity.com}}</ref> He moved to [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]]'s youth academy in 2008, where he played initially as a [[midfielder]], before changing position to [[centre-back]] for the [[S.L. Benfica Juniors|junior side]] until 2015.<ref name=Dias10facts/> In the same year, on 30 September, he made his professional debut with [[S.L. Benfica B|Benfica B]] in a [[2015–16 LigaPro]] match against [[G.D. Chaves|Chaves]].{{citation needed|date=June 2025}} On 7 March 2016, [[Rui Vitória]] called 18-year-old Dias for Benfica's [[UEFA Champions League]] Round of 16-second leg tie against [[FC Zenit Saint Petersburg|Zenit Saint Petersburg]] after three of his four main centre-backs were unable to make the trip to Russia.<ref>{{cite news|date=7 March 2016|title=Rui Vitória leva Rúben Dias na comitiva para a Champions|url=https://www.dn.pt/desporto/benfica/interior/crise-de-centrais-obriga-vitoria-a-chamar-jogador-da-equipa-b-para-jogo-com-zenit-5065150.html|newspaper=Diário de Notícias|access-date=8 June 2018}}</ref> The following season he helped the B team finish fourth; the club's highest ever position obtained in the [[2016–17 LigaPro|second division]]. He also helped the junior team reach the final of the [[2016–17 UEFA Youth League]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefayouthleague/history/season=2017/index.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829213438/http://www.uefa.com/uefayouthleague/history/season=2017/index.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=29 August 2017|title=Salzburg succeed Chelsea as Youth League winners|date=24 April 2017|publisher=UEFA|access-date=24 April 2017}}</ref>

===Benfica===
[[File:Rubén Dias Benfica-Zenit UCL201920 (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|Dias playing for [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] in 2019]]

On 16 September 2017, Dias debuted for the first team in a [[Primeira Liga]] match against [[Boavista F.C.|Boavista]]. After two months of impressive displays,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.teamtalk.com/news/benfica-boss-talks-up-talents-of-young-man-utd-target|title=Benfica boss talks up talents of young Man Utd target|date=31 October 2017|website=TeamTalk|access-date=31 October 2017}}</ref> including two games against [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in the [[2017–18 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]], he underwent surgery due to [[appendicitis]], sidelining him for a month.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.slbenfica.pt/en-us/agora/noticias/2017_2018/11/17/ruben-dias-operado-apendicite-jogador-benfica-futebol|title=Ruben Dias underwent surgery and will be out of Benfica's squad|date=17 November 2017|publisher=S.L. Benfica|access-date=17 November 2017}}</ref> He scored his first goal for [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] in a [[Taça da Liga]] encounter (2–2) against [[Vitória F.C.|Vitória de Setúbal]] on 29 December 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.noticiasaominuto.com/desporto/924432/ruben-dias-cabeceou-para-a-igualdade-no-bonfim|title=Rúben Dias cabeceou para a igualdade no Bonfim|date=29 December 2017|newspaper=Notícias ao Minuto|access-date=29 December 2017}}</ref> On 3 February 2018, he scored his first goal in the [[Primeira Liga]] against [[Rio Ave F.C.|Rio Ave]] (5–1).<ref>[https://www.slbenfica.pt/es-es/agora/media-list/videos/2017-2018/sporinvest/sr-match-11971930/sl-benfica-ruben-dias-aos-83-sl-benfica-41-rio-ave-fc GOL: RUBEN DIAS 83' SL BENFICA 4–1 RIO AVE FC]; SLBenfica.pt, 3 February 2018</ref> At the end of the season, he was voted Primeira Liga's best young player of the year.<ref name="best young player">{{cite news|url=https://maisfutebol.iol.pt/premios/benfica/liga-ruben-dias-vence-premio-para-jogador-jovem-do-ano|title=Liga: Rúben Dias vence prémio de jogador jovem do ano|date=6 July 2018|website=Maisfutebol|access-date=9 July 2018}}</ref>

After heavy speculation linking Dias to a big money move to French side [[Olympique Lyonnais|Lyon]], he extended his contract with Benfica until 2023.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.abola.pt/Nnh/Noticias/Ver/746377|title=Rúben Dias Renova até 2023|url-status=dead|date=22 August 2018|newspaper=A Bola|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822213712/https://www.abola.pt/Nnh/Noticias/Ver/746377|archive-date=22 August 2018|access-date=3 September 2018}}</ref> On 2 November 2019, Dias played his 100th game for the club and scored the opening goal against Rio Ave in a 2–0 home victory.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://desporto.sapo.pt/futebol/primeira-liga/artigos/ruben-dias-e-os-100-jogos-pelo-benfica-nem-nos-meus-melhores-sonhos | title = Rúben Dias e os 100 jogos pelo Benfica: "Nem nos meus melhores sonhos"| publisher = Sapo | language = pt | date = 2 November 2019 | access-date = 26 September 2020}}</ref>

On 26 September 2020, Dias scored the opening goal against [[Moreirense F.C.|Moreirense]] in a 2–0 win.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Benfica 2 – 0 Moreirense|url=https://www.slbenfica.pt/pt-pt/jogos/direto|access-date=26 September 2020|publisher=S.L. Benfica|language=pt}}</ref> After the game, manager [[Jorge Jesus]] admitted that it had likely been his last game for the club.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jn.pt/desporto/jorge-jesus-confirma-saida-de-ruben-dias-temos-pena-de-ve-lo-partir-e-tambem-tenho-culpa-12764313.html|title=Jorge Jesus confirma saída de Rúben Dias: "Temos pena de vê-lo partir. E também tenho culpa"|language=pt|website=[[Jornal de Notícias]]|date=26 September 2020|first=Sofia|last=Esteves Teixeira|access-date=29 September 2020}}</ref>

===Manchester City===
====2020–2021: Debut season and European final====
Dias signed for English [[Premier League]] club [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] on 29 September 2020 on a six-year contract, with an initial fee reported of €68&nbsp;million (£61.64&nbsp;million) that could rise to €71.6&nbsp;million with performance bonuses, plus [[Nicolás Otamendi]] being sent to Benfica in part-exchange for €15&nbsp;million bringing the net cost of the transaction to €56.6&nbsp;million (£51&nbsp;million).<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Benfica confirm sale and signing involving Man City – net sale of €56.6 million|url=https://www.si.com/soccer/manchestercity/news/benfica-confirm-sale-and-signing-involving-man-city-net-sale-of-56-6-million|date=27 September 2020|access-date=28 September 2020|magazine=Sports Illustrated}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=28 September 2020|title=Man City's £62m signing confirmed by Benfica, with current player moving other way|url=https://talksport.com/football/765888/man-city-ruben-dias-benfica-nicolas-otamendi-transfer-confirmed/|access-date=28 September 2020|website=talkSPORT}}</ref> On 3 October 2020, Dias made his league debut for City in a 1–1 away draw against [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Leeds 1–1 Man City: Rodrigo earns Leeds a draw against Man City |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/54305847 |work=BBC Sport |date=3 October 2020|access-date=3 October 2020}}</ref>

Dias was named the Manchester City Player of the Month for November 2020, following a series of very strong defensive performances.<ref>{{cite news|last=Clayton|first=David|title=Dias voted November Etihad Player of the Month|url=https://www.mancity.com/news/mens/etihad-player-of-the-month-november-winner-revealed-63743278|date=11 December 2020|access-date=8 January 2021|publisher=Manchester City F.C.}}</ref> On 27 February 2021, Dias scored his first goal for City in a 2–1 home league win over [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Manchester City 2–1 West Ham United: Pep Guardiola's side claim 20th straight win |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/56135047 |work=BBC Sport |date=27 February 2021|access-date=27 February 2021}}</ref> He was praised as being a key factor in Manchester City regaining the Premier League title that season by bringing composure, leadership and stability back to the defence.<ref>{{cite news|title=Manchester City win Premier League title after Manchester United lose to Leicester |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/56964843 |website=BBC Sport |date=27 February 2021|access-date=12 May 2021}}</ref> Dias won the [[FWA Footballer of the Year]] for the 2020–21 season, who described him as a "comfortable winner" ahead of [[Harry Kane]] and [[Kevin De Bruyne]], and becoming the first defender to win the award since [[Steve Nicol]] in the 1988–89 season.<ref name="BBC FOTY" /> He was also named Manchester City's Player of the Season<ref>{{cite web|last=MCFCCityTV|title=Dias named Etihad Player of the Season|url=https://www.mancity.com/citytv/mens/etihad-player-of-the-season-ruben-dias-63757447|date=24 May 2021|access-date=25 May 2021|publisher=Manchester Cuty F.C.}}</ref> and the [[Premier League Player of the Season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/2164971|title=Dias named EA SPORTS Player of the Season |publisher=Premier League|date=5 June 2021|access-date=5 June 2021}}</ref>

====2022–present: Consecutive league titles and Treble====
[[File:RubenDiasCity2023.jpg|thumb|upright|Dias with [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in 2023]]
On 15 September 2021, Dias captained Manchester City for the first time, providing an assist for [[Jack Grealish]] in a 6–3 home [[2021–22 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] win against [[RB Leipzig]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Dias to be one of Man City's five captains this season|publisher=Sky Sports|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11679/12410930/ruben-dias-pep-guardiola-makes-man-city-defender-one-of-his-five-captains-this-season|date=18 September 2021|access-date=18 September 2021}}</ref> On 1 December, Dias opened the scoring in Manchester City's 2–1 victory over [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]], with his first goal from outside the box in his career.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.jn.pt/desporto/manchester-city-vence-com-golos-portugueses-14371710.html|title=Manchester City vence com golos portugueses|newspaper=[[Jornal de Notícias]]|language=pt|date=1 December 2021|access-date=1 December 2021}}</ref>

On 4 March 2022, Manchester City manager [[Pep Guardiola]] announced that Dias had suffered an hamstring injury, his first injury in five years, leading him to miss two months of the season, which included the second [[Manchester Derby]] of the season, Manchester City's second leg of their [[2021–22 UEFA Champions League knockout phase#Round of 16|Champions League round of 16 tie]] against [[Sporting CP]] and [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]]'s [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification – UEFA second round|qualification play-offs]] for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.record.pt/internacional/paises/inglaterra/man--city/detalhe/ruben-dias-vai-parar-quatro-a-seis-semanas-por-lesao|title=Problema para a seleção: Rúben Dias vai parar quatro a seis semanas por lesão}}</ref> He made his return from injury on 20 April, replacing [[Nathan Aké]] in the 46th minute in a 3–0 victory over [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ojogo.pt/internacional/artigo/ruben-dias-regressa-bernardo-silva-marca-e-manchester-city-volta-a-ser-lider-na-premier-league/14786685/|title=Rúben Dias regressa, Bernardo Silva marca e Manchester City volta a ser líder na Premier League |date=20 April 2022 }}</ref> On 7 May, Dias suffered another hamstring injury during a match against [[Newcastle United]], sidelining him for the remainder of the season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abola.pt/nnh/2022-05-08/manchester-city-guardiola-confirma-ruben-dias-nao-joga-mais-esta-epoca/940163|title=GUARDIOLA CONFIRMA: RÚBEN DIAS NÃO JOGA MAIS ESTA ÉPOCA}}</ref>

Over the course of the [[2022–23 Manchester City F.C. season|2022–23 campaign]], Dias started and completed almost every minute for Manchester City, playing a major part in their campaign, as City secured their first ever Champions League trophy and complete a [[Treble (association football)|continental treble]], following a 1–0 victory against [[Inter Milan]] in the [[2023 UEFA Champions League final|Champions League final]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/65845807|title=Manchester City 1–0 Inter Milan|website=BBC Sport|date=10 June 2023}}</ref>

On 22 August 2025, Dias signed a new four-year contract, keeping him at Manchester City until the summer of 2029.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mancity.com/news/mens/ruben-dias-signs-new-manchester-city-contract-63891443 |title=Dias extends stay at City with new deal |publisher=Manchester City F.C. |date=22 August 2025 |access-date=22 August 2025}}</ref>

==International career==
===2013–2018: Youth level and first international tournament===
Dias represented the [[Portugal national under-17 football team|Under-17]] side at the [[2014 UEFA European Under-17 Championship]]. Two years later, he served as captain to the [[Portugal national under-19 football team|under-19]] squad at the [[2016 UEFA European Under-19 Championship]]. The following year, Dias served as captain to the [[Portugal national under-20 football team|under-20]] team at the [[2017 FIFA U-20 World Cup|2017 U-20 World Cup]], which lost to [[Uruguay national under-20 football team|Uruguay]] 5–4 on penalties in the quarterfinals. On 5 September 2017, he made his debut for the [[Portugal national under-21 football team|Under-21]] in a [[2019 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification]] match against [[Wales national under-21 football team|Wales]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/tournaments/mens/u20worldcup/origin1904-p.cxm.fifa.com/tournaments/mens/u20worldcup/fifa-u-20-world-cup-poland-2019|title=FIFA U-20 World Cup Poland 2019|publisher=FIFA|access-date=5 September 2017}}{{Dead link|date=April 2025}}</ref>

Ahead of international friendly matches against [[Egypt national football team|Egypt]] and the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]], Dias was called up to the [[Portugal national football team|senior side]] by Portugal coach [[Fernando Santos (footballer, born 1954)|Fernando Santos]] on 15 March 2018. However, four days later, he was dropped from the squad after picking up right ankle sprain.<ref>{{Cite web|first=Luís Pedro|last=Ferreira|title=Benfica: Rúben Dias tem entorse, seleção decide dispensa|url=http://www.maisfutebol.iol.pt/geral/19-03-2018/benfica-ruben-dias-tem-entorse-selecao-decide-dispensa|website=Mais Futebol|date=19 March 2018|access-date=1 April 2025|language=pt}}</ref> On 17 May 2018, Dias was named in Portugal's 23-man squad for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup|FIFA World Cup]] in Russia.<ref>{{Cite web|first=Stephen|last=Crawford|title=Revealed: Every World Cup 2018 squad {{!}} Final 23-man lists|url=https://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/revealed-every-world-cup-2018-squad-23-man-preliminary-lists/oa0atsduflsv1nsf6oqk576rb|website=[[Goal (website)|Goal]]|date=4 June 2018|access-date=1 April 2025}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Nearly half Portugal's Euro squad to miss World Cup|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/nearly-half-portugals-euro-squad-to-miss-world-cup/p10dugwu4|website=[[SBS World News]]|date=18 May 2018|access-date=1 April 2025}}</ref> Eleven days later, he made his international debut in a friendly match against [[Tunisia national football team|Tunisia]].<ref>{{Cite web|first=Bruno José|last=Ferreira|title=Portugal-Tunísia (equipas): Ruben Dias estreia-se na seleção A|url=https://maisfutebol.iol.pt/geral/28-05-2018/portugal-tunisia-equipas-ruben-dias-estreia-se-na-selecao-a|website=Mais Futebol|date=28 May 2018|access-date=1 April 2025|language=pt}}</ref> Despite being present at the World Cup, he did not feature in any of Portugal's four matches in the competition.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Rúben Dias|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/players/player/384752/|url-status=dead|publisher=[[FIFA]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180622165531/https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/players/player/384752/|archive-date=22 June 2018}}</ref>

===2018–2022: Nations League title and subsequent tournaments===
Following the World Cup, Dias began establishing himself at centre-back, overtaking [[José Fonte]]'s place alongside [[Pepe (footballer, born 1983)|Pepe]], featuring in all of Portugal's [[2018–19 UEFA Nations League]] matches, helping Portugal reach the [[2019 UEFA Nations League final]] on home soil. On 9 June, Portugal defeated the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] 1–0 in the tournament's final, with Dias being named man of the match.<ref>{{cite news|last=Law|first=Matt|title=Result: Goncalo Guedes scores winner as Portugal land UEFA Nations League title|url=https://www.sportsmole.co.uk/football/portugal/uefa-nations-league/result/result-guedes-scores-winner-as-portugal-land-nations-league-title_361579.html|access-date=1 April 2025|website=Sports Mole|date=5 July 2019}}</ref> For his performances throughout the competition, he was named in the "[[2019 UEFA Nations League Finals#Awards|Team of the Tournament]]".<ref name=nations>{{cite news|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefanationsleague/news/0253-0d821e23494c-f0c94c4974b3-1000--uefa-nations-league-finals-team-of-the-tournament/|title=UEFA Nations League Finals: Team of the Tournament|publisher=UEFA|date=10 June 2019|access-date=11 June 2019}}</ref>

On 17 November 2020, Dias scored his first international goals during the [[2020–21 UEFA Nations League]], with a brace in a 3–2 victory against [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Krušelj|first=Dražen|date=18 November 2020|title=Zaslužili smo ostanak! Naš gard bio je jasan odmah nakon što je Lovren zagalamio na Pašalića...|url=https://sportske.jutarnji.hr/sn/nogomet/reprezentacija/zasluzili-smo-ostanak-nas-gard-bio-je-jasan-odmah-nakon-sto-je-lovren-zagalamio-na-pasalica-15031949|access-date=18 November 2020|website=Sportske novosti|language=hr}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Hina|date=17 November 2020|title=Drama za Hrvate: Portugal slavio u Splitu, ali Vatreni ostaju u elitnom razredu|url=https://www.vecernji.hr/sport/uzivo-od-20-45-hrvatska-odlucuje-o-svojoj-sudbini-u-elitnom-razredu-lige-nacija-1446869|access-date=18 November 2020|website=Večernji list|language=hr}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Hrnčić|first=Fabijan|date=18 November 2020|title=Luka čestitao Kovi: Bravo, brate|url=https://www.24sata.hr/sport/luka-cestitao-kovi-bravo-brate-728973|access-date=19 November 2020|website=24sata|language=hr}}</ref> He was selected in Portugal's squad for [[UEFA Euro 2020]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=Portugal's full 26-man Euro 2020 squad|url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/4210925/2021/06/02/portugals-full-26-man-euro-2020-squad/|access-date=21 June 2021|website=The Athletic}}</ref> On 19 June 2021, he scored an own goal in the 35th minute in a 4–2 loss to [[Germany national football team|Germany]] at Euro 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Portugal vs. Germany {{!}} Football Match Report|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/report/_/gameId/560322 |publisher=ESPN|date=19 June 2021|access-date=21 June 2021}}</ref>{{Better source needed|date=April 2025}} He appeared in all of Portugal's matches, being eventually eliminated at the round of 16, following a 1–0 loss to [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://observador.pt/especiais/euro-2020-grupo-f-portugal-o-campeao-que-leva-mala-tabaco-e-qualidade-como-nunca-para-so-voltar-daqui-a-um-mes/|title=Euro 2020 (grupo F). Portugal, o campeão que leva mala, tabaco e qualidade como nunca para só voltar daqui a um mês|trans-title=Euro 2020 (group F). Portugal, the champions who take suitcase, cigarettes and talent like never before to return only a month later|newspaper=Observador|first=Mariana|last=Fernandes|language=pt|date=10 June 2021|access-date=1 September 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro-2020/match/2024479--belgium-vs-portugal/postmatch/report/|title=Belgium 1–0 Portugal: Holders dethroned by Thorgan Hazard|publisher=UEFA|date=27 June 2021|access-date=1 September 2021}}{{dead link|date=March 2025|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>

===2022–present: Second Nations League title===
[[File:RubenDiasPortugal.jpg|thumb|upright|Dias during a press conference with [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] in 2024]]
In October 2022, he was named in Portugal's preliminary 55-man squad for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] in Qatar,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportskeeda.com/football/rumor-portugal-reportedly-announce-provisional-55-man-squad-2022-fifa-world-cup-liverpool-star-receives-surprise-call|title=Portugal reportedly name provisional 55-man squad for 2022 FIFA World Cup; Liverpool star receives surprise call up|website=Sportskeeda|publisher=[[Nazara Technologies]]|first=Dakir Mohammed|last=Thanveer|date=25 October 2022|access-date=9 November 2022}}</ref> before being included in the final 26-man squad for the tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://desporto.sapo.pt/futebol/mundial/artigos/os-26-convocados-de-portugal-para-o-mundial2022|title=Os 26 convocados de Portugal: Gonçalo Ramos, António Silva, Otávio e Matheus Nunes chamados|trans-title=Portugal select 26: Gonçalo Ramos, António Silva, Otávio and Matheus Nunes called|publisher=[[SAPO (company)|SAPO]]|language=pt|date=10 November 2022|access-date=10 November 2022}}</ref> He played almost every minute of their campaign, as they were knocked out of the tournament after losing 1–0 in the quarter-finals against [[Morocco national football team|Morocco]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=10 December 2022 |title=Morocco 1–0 Portugal: World Cup 2022 quarter-final – as it happened |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2022/dec/10/morocco-portugal-world-cup-2022-quarter-final-live |access-date=11 December 2022 |website=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref>

On 11 September 2023, during a [[UEFA Euro 2024 qualifying]] match against [[Luxembourg national football team|Luxembourg]] at home, Dias earned his 50th cap, starting in Portugal's 9–0 victory, their biggest win in international history.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://maisfutebol.iol.pt/portugal/selecao-nacional/portugal-9-0-luxemburgo-cronica|title=Portugal 9–0 Luxemburgo (crónica)|trans-title=Portugal 9–0 Luxembourg (report)|website=Mais Futebol|publisher=IOL|first=Pedro|last=Lemos|language=pt|date=11 September 2023|access-date=11 September 2023}}</ref>

On 21 May 2024, Dias was named in Portugal's squad for [[UEFA Euro 2024]] in Germany.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cx88ljwp5x8o|title=Ronaldo named in Portugal squad for Euro 2024|date=21 May 2024|access-date=3 July 2024|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> He started in the team's first two matches against [[Czech Republic national football team|the Czech Republic]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/match/2036172--portugal-vs-czechia/lineups/|title=Portugal vs Czechia: Line-ups|access-date=3 July 2024|publisher=UEFA}}</ref> and [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/match/2036183--turkiye-vs-portugal/lineups/|title=Türkiye vs Portugal: Line-ups|access-date=3 July 2024|publisher=UEFA}}</ref> before being rested for the final [[UEFA Euro 2024 Group F|Group F]] match against [[Georgia national football team|Georgia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/match/2036196--georgia-vs-portugal/|title=Georgia vs Portugal|access-date=3 July 2024|publisher=UEFA}}</ref> He was restored to the starting line-up for Portugal's [[UEFA Euro 2024 knockout stage#Round of 16|round of 16]] match against [[Slovenia national football team|Slovenia]] and played 117 minutes before being substituted for [[Rúben Neves]] as Portugal won 3–0 in a [[penalty shootout]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/match/2036201--portugal-vs-slovenia/lineups/|title=Portugal vs Slovenia: Line-ups|access-date=3 July 2024|publisher=UEFA}}</ref> Portugal were eliminated in the quarter-finals to [[France national football team|France]] after losing 5–3 in another penalty shootout.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cy79llev4znt|title=Portugal 0–0 France (France win 5–3 on pens)|website=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC|first=Emma|last=Sanders|date=5 July 2024|access-date=6 July 2024}}</ref>

On 20 May 2025, Dias was selected for Portugal’s [[2025 UEFA Nations League Finals]] [[2025 UEFA Nations League Finals squads#Portugal|squad]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Convocatória para Liga das Nações divulgada |trans-title=Nations League squad announced |url=https://www.fpf.pt/pt/News/Todas-as-notícias/Notícia/news/50645 |website=[[Portuguese Football Federation]] |language=pt |access-date=26 May 2025 |date=20 May 2025}}</ref> He and his team would go on to win the tournament [[2025 UEFA Nations League final|5–3 in a penalty shootout]] over rivals [[Spain national football team|Spain]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/6408339/2025/06/08/spain-portugal-yamal-mendes-ronaldo/|title=Spain 2 Portugal 2 (3–5 on pens): Mendes vs Yamal, Ronaldo being Ronaldo, and World Cup chances|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|first1=Tim|last1=Spiers|first2=Dermot|last2=Corrigan|first3=Stu|last3=James|date=8 June 2025|access-date=8 June 2025}}</ref>

==Player profile==
[[File:Rúben Dias WC2022.jpg|thumb|upright|Dias at the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]]]]

===Style of play===
Dias is a physically strong, right-footed [[centre-back]] who usually features on the left-hand side of central defence, due to his comfort in passing the ball with both feet. He is able to pass in different directions, whether to a teammate on the same side, switching to the opposite side, or making vertical line-breaking passes. Combining his two-footedness with a very good passing range, Dias can dictate play in any direction from the back.

His strength on the ball when shielding it away from forwards running down his channel. Dias is very calm on the ball too and rarely finds himself in a heap of pressure. Dias is extremely proficient at passing, especially in longer passes, as his passing quality and ability is able to help his team retain possession.

Dias is also dominant in the air, winning most of his aerial duels, as he looks to target his teammates and find them on a regular basis. He also uses his size to help him contest well in tackles, as he is also great at bodying up on players to win the ball back. He has a good-timing as he is able to anticipate a player's action or react for a "last-ditch" challenge.<ref name="Styleofplay2">{{Cite web |title=Player Analysis: Rúben Dias |date=14 February 2021 |url=https://breakingthelines.com/player-analysis/player-analysis-ruben-dias/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.betvictor.com/en-gb/sports/football/european-scout-report-joao-felix-and-ruben-dias/|title=European Scout Report: João Felix And Rúben Dias|website=BetVictor Blog|access-date=27 October 2021|archive-date=29 October 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211029013944/https://blog.betvictor.com/en-gb/sports/football/european-scout-report-joao-felix-and-ruben-dias/|url-status=dead}}</ref>

===Reception===
His Manchester City manager [[Pep Guardiola]], stated that "Dias a center back who leads the defensive line and in doing so helps others to make good decisions, the same happens in relation to midfielders [...] he is a player capable of living every moment of the game [...] always being focused on what he has to do and he makes his partner better."<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.record.pt/internacional/paises/inglaterra/man--city/detalhe/guardiola-rendido-a-ruben-dias-e-o-que-acontece-quando-te-tornas-um-incrivel-central|title=Guardiola rendido a Rúben Dias: "É o que acontece quando te tornas um incrível central"|website=record.pt}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.record.pt/internacional/paises/inglaterra/man--city/detalhe/guardiola-rendido-a-caracteristica-de-ruben-dias-nao-e-facil-encontra-la-num-jogador-de-23-anos|title=Guardiola rendido a característica de Rúben Dias: "Não é fácil encontrá-la num jogador de 23 anos"|website=record.pt}}</ref> [[José Mourinho]] would praise Dias as the "best centre-back in world [...] for the [[Premier League]], [he's] gaining another level of experience, knowledge".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.record.pt/internacional/competicoes-de-selecoes/europeu/euro-2020/detalhe/mourinho-ruben-dias-e-o-melhor-central-do-mundo|title=Mourinho: "Rúben Dias é o melhor central do mundo"|website=record.pt}}</ref>

Former Manchester United defender [[Gary Neville]], stated that "Dias is the type of player who makes the whole team feel safe." Meanwhile, former [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] defender [[Jamie Carragher]] would compare Dias to legendary [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] defender [[Carles Puyol]], stating that "the amount of interceptions" during a [[UEFA Champions League]] match reminded him of legendary Premier League defender [[John Terry]], while also praising his "leadership skills".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.record.pt/internacional/paises/inglaterra/man--city/detalhe/carragher-e-neville-consideram-ruben-dias-o-melhor-jogador-da-premier-league-excecional|title=Carragher e Neville consideram Rúben Dias o melhor jogador da Premier League: "Excecional"|website=record.pt}}</ref>

==Personal life==
[[File:Ruben Dias, 14 November 2024 (2).jpg|thumb|upright|Dias in 2024]]
Dias was in a relationship with Portuguese singer [[April Ivy]] from 2018 to 2021.<ref>{{Cite web|date=10 September 2021|title=Rúben Dias e April Ivy separam-se|url=https://infocul.pt/ruben-dias-e-april-ivy-separam-se/|access-date=10 September 2021|website=infocul.pt|language=pt}}</ref> In March 2025, [[Gary Lineker]] mentioned in an online video that Dias was now dating British television presenter [[Maya Jama]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.capitalfm.com/news/maya-jama-new-boyfriend-ruben-dias-gary-lineker/|title=Maya Jama reacts to Gary Lineker "outing" who her new boyfriend is|last=Reynolds|first=Abbie|work=[[Capital (radio network)|Capital]]|date=12 March 2025|access-date=19 March 2025}}</ref>

